1
00:01:36,527 --> 00:01:38,961
- How much?
- Six million.

2
00:01:39,048 --> 00:01:41,362
- But that's ridiculous.
- It's worth 30.

3
00:01:41,447 --> 00:01:44,122
It'll have to be split up.
We'll lose at least 40% of it.

4
00:01:44,208 --> 00:01:45,605
Enough!

5
00:01:45,688 --> 00:01:46,605
What?

6
00:01:46,688 --> 00:01:47,922
I am Clouseau,

7
00:01:48,008 --> 00:01:50,879
and justice will be done
in the name of the "lew."

8
00:07:01,480 --> 00:07:04,591
One year ago today,
Inspector Jacques Clouseau,

9
00:07:04,680 --> 00:07:08,795
the Police Academy's most
illustrious graduate, disappeared.

10
00:07:08,881 --> 00:07:12,036
We felt it appropriate to broadcast
this commemorative program

11
00:07:12,121 --> 00:07:15,471
from the Academy, where
a new generation of police officers

12
00:07:15,561 --> 00:07:17,635
are about to receive their shields.

13
00:07:17,721 --> 00:07:20,199
The question
on every Frenchman's mind is,

14
00:07:20,282 --> 00:07:23,993
"What has happened to
France's greatest detective?

15
00:07:24,082 --> 00:07:26,353
"Why haven't the authorities
been able to solve the mystery?"

16
00:07:27,482 --> 00:07:30,593
Tell the police commissioner
I want to see him.

17
00:07:30,683 --> 00:07:32,113
Oui, Monsieur Président.

18
00:07:35,403 --> 00:07:37,913
The president himself gave the order!

19
00:07:38,003 --> 00:07:40,874
And at 3:00 this morning,
the commissioner woke me up

20
00:07:40,964 --> 00:07:43,758
to say he was putting me in charge. Me!

21
00:07:44,845 --> 00:07:48,403
And I've got one month
to make Operation Paragon a success.

22
00:07:48,485 --> 00:07:50,558
Otherwise, I'll be back on the vice squad

23
00:07:50,645 --> 00:07:53,559
staking out pissoirs
for what is left of my career.

24
00:07:53,645 --> 00:07:54,803
Operation Paragon?

25
00:07:54,885 --> 00:07:57,123
Yes. The President's idea.

26
00:07:57,205 --> 00:07:59,715
If France's greatest detective is missing,

27
00:07:59,805 --> 00:08:02,240
then get the world's greatest detective
to find him.

28
00:08:02,326 --> 00:08:04,684
And how do you find
the world's greatest detective?

29
00:08:04,766 --> 00:08:07,680
By computer. The Commissioner's idea.

30
00:08:08,326 --> 00:08:09,920
Interpol has computer files

31
00:08:10,007 --> 00:08:12,561
on every law enforcement agency
in the world,

32
00:08:12,647 --> 00:08:16,882
and I am supposed to program
the computer to select Clouseau's clone.

33
00:08:16,967 --> 00:08:18,245
But Clouseau...

34
00:08:18,327 --> 00:08:20,837
You know he was an idiot,
and I know he was an idiot,

35
00:08:20,928 --> 00:08:24,125
but the rest of the world sees him
as a fearless deductive genius,

36
00:08:24,209 --> 00:08:25,442
another Sherlock Holmes,

37
00:08:25,529 --> 00:08:27,286
and that's the type of man
we are now looking for.

38
00:08:27,368 --> 00:08:28,526
Then you have a problem.

39
00:08:28,608 --> 00:08:31,959
Yes, because a man like this
might find Clouseau...

40
00:08:32,049 --> 00:08:33,719
A horrible thought.

41
00:08:34,689 --> 00:08:36,523
What's the alternative?

42
00:08:37,370 --> 00:08:38,560
I don't know.

43
00:08:39,570 --> 00:08:42,921
I'm damned if I do,
and I'm damned if I don't.

44
00:08:57,492 --> 00:08:59,849
A series 600 Huxley computer.

45
00:09:01,492 --> 00:09:04,047
You can program it by
voice command, you know.

46
00:09:04,132 --> 00:09:06,686
Ouais. Observe this. Activate.

47
00:09:09,133 --> 00:09:11,283
- Aldous.
- Ready, Dave.

48
00:09:12,453 --> 00:09:14,768
Aldous can even recognize people's voices.

49
00:09:14,853 --> 00:09:16,764
- Amazing.
- Elementary.

50
00:09:17,733 --> 00:09:21,051
Chief Inspector Dreyfus, Sûreté,
vital statistics, please.

51
00:09:21,174 --> 00:09:22,691
Coming up, Dave.

52
00:09:26,135 --> 00:09:28,208
- What's the delay?
- Lots of material.

53
00:09:28,375 --> 00:09:31,006
Well, just give me
an abbreviated version then.

54
00:09:31,095 --> 00:09:34,370
All right. Charles Larousse Dreyfus.

55
00:09:34,455 --> 00:09:38,526
Born Marseilles, April 1, 19...

56
00:09:38,616 --> 00:09:40,493
Skip that. Skip that.

57
00:09:40,576 --> 00:09:43,327
What is the subject's present occupation?

58
00:09:43,416 --> 00:09:45,567
Subject's present occupation...

59
00:09:45,657 --> 00:09:48,931
Chief Inspector, Criminal Division, Sûreté.

60
00:09:49,936 --> 00:09:51,170
How's his health?

61
00:09:51,377 --> 00:09:54,128
Last complete physical examination...

62
00:09:54,217 --> 00:09:56,771
January 7th, this year.

63
00:09:56,858 --> 00:09:58,768
Chronic hypertension.

64
00:09:58,857 --> 00:10:02,611
May, 1978, suffered nervous breakdown

65
00:10:02,698 --> 00:10:04,292
and was committed to the state mental...

66
00:10:04,378 --> 00:10:05,972
- Skip!
- Sorry.

67
00:10:06,059 --> 00:10:07,336
Do you want to ask him anything?

68
00:10:08,259 --> 00:10:09,372
Yes.

69
00:10:10,219 --> 00:10:12,490
What are the odds

70
00:10:12,579 --> 00:10:17,250
that the greatest detective in the world
will find Clouseau?

71
00:10:17,340 --> 00:10:19,534
Even money. Take your pick.

72
00:10:20,420 --> 00:10:24,611
Well, aren't you being slightly optimistic?

73
00:10:24,700 --> 00:10:26,131
Not at all.

74
00:10:26,221 --> 00:10:29,255
Why? Are you afraid
he'll drive you crazy again?

75
00:10:29,341 --> 00:10:31,131
Cool it, Aldous.

76
00:10:31,221 --> 00:10:34,375
Just responding with
an obvious observation.

77
00:10:34,462 --> 00:10:38,053
I hope I didn't offend you,
Inspector Dreyfus.

78
00:10:38,142 --> 00:10:39,452
Not at all.

79
00:10:40,142 --> 00:10:42,860
By the way, it's Chief Inspector Dreyfus.

80
00:10:43,982 --> 00:10:45,816
Shame on you, Aldous.

81
00:10:45,902 --> 00:10:48,620
Nobody's perfect. Have a happy day.

82
00:10:50,223 --> 00:10:51,173
Yes?

83
00:10:52,703 --> 00:10:54,461
Prisoner Steiger has arrived.

84
00:10:54,543 --> 00:10:55,896
Show him in.

85
00:10:55,984 --> 00:10:57,097
Come in.

86
00:11:01,744 --> 00:11:02,694
Wait outside.

87
00:11:04,665 --> 00:11:05,778
Sit down.

88
00:11:11,465 --> 00:11:15,340
Maurice Steiger...
15 years for bank robbery.

89
00:11:16,785 --> 00:11:18,259
How much was it?

90
00:11:18,426 --> 00:11:21,897
About 150 million,
give or take a few francs.

91
00:11:24,746 --> 00:11:26,536
And it's never been recovered.

92
00:11:28,627 --> 00:11:31,301
It must be hell, sitting in prison,

93
00:11:31,387 --> 00:11:34,585
dreaming about what
you could do with all that money.

94
00:11:34,668 --> 00:11:36,785
It's not so bad.

95
00:11:36,868 --> 00:11:40,023
I'm a model prisoner.
I come up for parole in six months.

96
00:11:40,348 --> 00:11:44,582
Yes, but there's always the chance
that the Parole Board will turn you down.

97
00:11:45,868 --> 00:11:46,818
I see.

98
00:11:47,309 --> 00:11:49,099
I tell you where the money is,

99
00:11:49,189 --> 00:11:51,263
you put in a good word
with the Parole Board.

100
00:11:51,909 --> 00:11:52,859
No.

101
00:11:52,950 --> 00:11:54,227
Listen...

102
00:11:55,069 --> 00:11:58,824
It took a computer genius to embezzle

103
00:11:58,910 --> 00:12:02,108
150 million francs from the Bank of France,

104
00:12:02,190 --> 00:12:05,061
and I have a problem

105
00:12:05,151 --> 00:12:07,301
that requires a computer genius.

106
00:12:07,391 --> 00:12:08,701
You help me solve that problem,

107
00:12:08,791 --> 00:12:11,061
and in 6 months' time, you'll be a free man,

108
00:12:11,151 --> 00:12:14,950
living out 150 million dreams,

109
00:12:15,032 --> 00:12:16,746
give or take a few dreams.

110
00:12:17,712 --> 00:12:19,022
What's your problem?

111
00:12:20,912 --> 00:12:22,910
Can you rig a computer

112
00:12:22,993 --> 00:12:26,103
so that no matter what I program into it,

113
00:12:26,193 --> 00:12:29,390
it will select the exact opposite?

114
00:12:29,473 --> 00:12:31,230
Black is white? Day is night?

115
00:12:31,313 --> 00:12:32,591
Exactly.

116
00:12:33,193 --> 00:12:34,950
What sort of computer?

117
00:12:37,914 --> 00:12:39,344
A Huxley 600.

118
00:12:40,555 --> 00:12:42,628
There is only one of those in this country.

119
00:12:42,715 --> 00:12:45,585
How are you going to get me into Interpol?

120
00:12:45,675 --> 00:12:46,985
I can't.

121
00:12:47,075 --> 00:12:49,225
Then how do you expect me to rig it?

122
00:12:49,315 --> 00:12:52,546
I don't. I expect you to tell me how to rig it.

123
00:13:04,677 --> 00:13:06,194
The President has just arrived,

124
00:13:06,277 --> 00:13:08,831
and is being greeted by
Sergeant Duval of the Sûreté

125
00:13:08,917 --> 00:13:11,111
and Secretary General Dulong of Interpol.

126
00:13:11,197 --> 00:13:12,834
And now we switch to Michelle Chauvin,

127
00:13:12,918 --> 00:13:15,308
who is about to interview
the star of these proceedings.

128
00:13:15,397 --> 00:13:16,588
Good morning, Michelle.

129
00:13:17,238 --> 00:13:20,076
This is Chief Inspector Dreyfus
of the Sûreté.

130
00:13:20,158 --> 00:13:22,189
You are the one who is
going to program Aldous

131
00:13:22,278 --> 00:13:23,828
to select Clouseau's successor?

132
00:13:23,918 --> 00:13:24,868
Yes.

133
00:13:25,479 --> 00:13:26,669
No.

134
00:13:26,759 --> 00:13:29,510
He is not going to be Clouseau's successor.

135
00:13:29,599 --> 00:13:31,269
Why not a she?

136
00:13:31,359 --> 00:13:32,550
What?

137
00:13:32,640 --> 00:13:34,713
Well, couldn't it just as easily be a woman,

138
00:13:34,800 --> 00:13:37,431
or are you purposely
programming it to be a man?

139
00:13:38,400 --> 00:13:42,471
No, no. We are just trying to find
the best, the most qualified...

140
00:13:42,560 --> 00:13:44,558
The most like Clouseau?

141
00:13:44,640 --> 00:13:45,590
Yes.

142
00:13:47,521 --> 00:13:49,235
To paraphrase an old saying,

143
00:13:49,321 --> 00:13:52,115
set a great detective
to find a great detective.

144
00:13:52,201 --> 00:13:56,393
Exactly. But he or she
will not be Clouseau's successor.

145
00:13:56,482 --> 00:13:59,517
I mean, they won't be
going to work for the Sûreté...

146
00:13:59,602 --> 00:14:00,835
I hope.

147
00:14:00,923 --> 00:14:02,200
Excuse me.

148
00:14:03,123 --> 00:14:04,880
The President has just arrived.

149
00:14:05,403 --> 00:14:07,641
In a few moments, Aldous the computer

150
00:14:07,723 --> 00:14:09,033
will select from the files

151
00:14:09,123 --> 00:14:11,754
of all the law enforcement
agencies in the world

152
00:14:11,844 --> 00:14:13,677
the one man or woman

153
00:14:13,764 --> 00:14:16,001
most qualified to solve the disappearance

154
00:14:16,084 --> 00:14:17,437
of France's greatest detective.

155
00:14:17,524 --> 00:14:19,238
And screw up my entire life.

156
00:14:19,324 --> 00:14:20,482
Just over a year ago,

157
00:14:20,564 --> 00:14:22,114
while investigating yet another theft

158
00:14:22,204 --> 00:14:24,322
of the famous diamond, the Pink Panther,

159
00:14:24,404 --> 00:14:27,318
Inspector Clouseau seemed to
vanish from the face of the earth,

160
00:14:27,405 --> 00:14:30,559
leaving behind one of France's
greatest unsolved mysteries.

161
00:14:30,645 --> 00:14:32,916
Not to mention
the 4,000 francs he owes me.

162
00:14:33,006 --> 00:14:36,084
And now, working on the theory
that the best person to find Clouseau

163
00:14:36,166 --> 00:14:38,644
is someone almost exactly like Clouseau,

164
00:14:38,726 --> 00:14:42,317
Chief Inspector Dreyfus
will program Aldous the computer

165
00:14:42,406 --> 00:14:44,917
with a character profile
of Inspector Clouseau.

166
00:14:45,007 --> 00:14:47,681
That's going to put a hell of a strain
on poor old Aldous.

167
00:14:47,767 --> 00:14:49,644
Obviously, Mr. President,

168
00:14:49,728 --> 00:14:52,238
so as not to limit our choice,

169
00:14:52,328 --> 00:14:56,159
I will omit sex, height, weight,

170
00:14:56,248 --> 00:14:58,366
race, and nationality.

171
00:15:01,048 --> 00:15:03,526
- Ready, Aldous?
- Ready, Charles.

172
00:15:06,129 --> 00:15:08,923
Age... 61.

173
00:15:11,410 --> 00:15:12,763
Senior officer.

174
00:15:15,210 --> 00:15:16,487
I.Q...

175
00:15:21,251 --> 00:15:22,408
Genius.

176
00:15:25,651 --> 00:15:27,562
Specialities...

177
00:15:27,651 --> 00:15:32,169
Judo, kung fu, Okinawan weaponry,

178
00:15:33,931 --> 00:15:35,808
karate expert...

179
00:15:38,092 --> 00:15:39,565
Black belt.

180
00:15:43,573 --> 00:15:47,251
Expert ma... Ma...

181
00:15:48,493 --> 00:15:49,890
Marksman.

182
00:15:51,493 --> 00:15:52,683
Fearless.

183
00:15:53,774 --> 00:15:55,084
Courageous.

184
00:15:57,934 --> 00:15:59,528
A born leader.

185
00:16:01,975 --> 00:16:03,088
Sir.

186
00:16:03,655 --> 00:16:05,292
Is that it, Chief?

187
00:16:07,335 --> 00:16:08,406
Select.

188
00:16:08,616 --> 00:16:10,253
Coming right up.

189
00:16:19,017 --> 00:16:20,207
What is he humming?

190
00:16:20,296 --> 00:16:23,210
It sounds like Moon River...

191
00:16:23,297 --> 00:16:24,695
Backwards!

192
00:16:27,177 --> 00:16:29,687
Chief Inspector Dreyfus
is obviously nervous.

193
00:16:29,777 --> 00:16:31,534
The President and the Commissioner

194
00:16:31,618 --> 00:16:33,855
are waiting tensely
as the moment draws near.

195
00:16:33,938 --> 00:16:35,575
Ladies and gentlemen,

196
00:16:35,658 --> 00:16:37,895
after thoroughly searching the records

197
00:16:37,978 --> 00:16:43,097
of 13,623,055 candidates,

198
00:16:43,699 --> 00:16:46,570
I have come up with your man.

199
00:16:46,779 --> 00:16:47,892
It's a man.

200
00:16:47,980 --> 00:16:49,453
From the 11th Precinct

201
00:16:49,539 --> 00:16:51,929
of the New York City Police Department,

202
00:16:52,020 --> 00:16:55,294
I give you... A little drum roll, please...

203
00:17:05,741 --> 00:17:06,899
Got a light, big boy?

204
00:17:07,701 --> 00:17:11,859
Cliff, broads don't call
guys "big boy" anymore.

205
00:17:14,262 --> 00:17:15,735
Right, Charlie.

206
00:17:17,743 --> 00:17:19,500
I thought you didn't smoke.

207
00:17:19,582 --> 00:17:22,060
I think it kinda goes with the look.

208
00:17:22,142 --> 00:17:23,300
Thanks.

209
00:17:31,424 --> 00:17:33,497
I don't believe it!
He's gonna blow their cover!

210
